<h1>Details</h1>

<p>The history of banking, especially the terminology, is very closely tied to medieval French and Latin. Many of the core concepts (esp. the ones underlying 'debit' and 'credit') were developed in the high and late middle ages.<br/>
    Though 'modern' accounting practices are popularly traced to the Renaissance, most notably in the Venetian usage of double-entry bookkeeping and Arabic/Hindu numerals, the roots of accounting philosophy can be traced to at least the 14th century, and likely earlier.
</p>

